America as a Vector Sum of Government and Entrepreneurial Forces
My hypothesis is that technology compounds more quickly than the government=
 ossifies, and that entrepreneurship in a broad sense has overtaken institu=
tions as the prime mover of American exceptionalism.=C2=A0=C2=A0
One (very oversimplified) way to think of progress is as a vector sum of go=
vernment and entrepreneurial forces.=C2=A0
A vector is a quantity that has both a magnitude and a direction, like velo=
city (speed in a specific direction) or force (strength applied in a partic=
ular direction). You can think about it like an arrow of a certain length (=
magnitude) pointing a certain way (direction). A vector sum is what you get=
 when you add the vectors up.=C2=A0
Government and entrepreneurship can pull in various directions at various s=
trengths. When they=E2=80=99re both pulling in the same direction - up and =
to the right - progress happens more quickly. But even if the government st=
agnates, a strong entrepreneurial ecosystem can pull progress ahead on its =
own.=C2=A0
This may be easier to look at than imagine, so I asked Claude 3.5 Sonnet [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/1ace7344-dac4-4ff2-a112-1ceb887994cf?j=3DeyJ1=
IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] to make me a t=
oy model to play around with.=C2=A0
Imagine that entrepreneurship is pulling in the direction of progress at a =
magnitude of 50, and the government is pulling in the opposite direction at=
 a magnitude of 50. You end up with zero progress.=C2=A0
We can play with a bunch of different scenarios. Like what if the governmen=
t is completely ineffective (0 magnitude) but entrepreneurship is maximally=
 effective (100 magnitude)? You get a progress magnitude of 100. Or what if=
 the government is slowing down progress with 50 magnitude, but entrepreneu=
rship is pulling it forward at 100 magnitude? You get a progress magnitude =
of 50.=C2=A0
